

<section>
  <title>Fractions</title>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <ol>
        \itemsep=\fill

        <li>
          <p>
            Add the fractions, and simplify if possible:
            <m>\frac{5}{14}+\frac{7}{14}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Add the fractions, and simplify if possible:
            <m>\frac{17}{x} + \frac{3}{x}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Get a common denominator and combine the fractions:
            <m>\frac{3}{10} + \frac{8}{15}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Get a common denominator and combine the fractions:
            <m>\frac{3}{7} + \frac{2}{11}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Get a common denominator and combine the fractions:
            <m>\frac{3}{7} + \frac{x}{11}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Get a common denominator and combine the fractions:
            <m>\frac{3}{x} + \frac{x}{11}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Multiply the fractions, and simplify if possible:
            <m>\frac{-5}{3}\cdot \frac{7}{10}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Multiply the fractions, and simplify if possible:
            <m>\frac{x}{2}\cdot \frac{x}{7}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Multiply the fractions, and simplify if possible:
            <m>\frac{3x}{2}\cdot \frac{-13}{5x}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Simplify until you get a single fraction,
            with no compound fractions:
            <m>x\left(\frac{1+\sfrac 1x}{x+\sfrac 1x}\right)</m> \handoutfill
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{5+7}{14} = \frac{12}{14} = \frac{6}{7}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{17+3}{x}= \frac{20}{x}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{9}{30} + \frac{16}{30} = \frac{25}{30} = \frac{5}{6}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{33}{77} + \frac{14}{77} = \frac{47}{77}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{33}{77} + \frac{7x}{77} = \frac{33+7x}{77}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{33}{11x}+\frac{x^2}{11x} = \frac{33+x^2}{11x}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              There are two ways you can do this.
              Multiply, then cancel:
              <me>
                \frac{-35}{30} = \frac{-35\div 5}{30\div 5} = \frac{-7}{6}
              </me>
              or you can cancel, then multiply second:
              <me>
                \frac{-\cancel{5}^{\textstyle 1}}{3}\cdot
                \frac{7}{\cancel{10}_{\textstyle{2}}}
                =\frac{-1\cdot 7}{3\cdot 2}=\frac{-7}{6}
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{x}{2}\cdot \frac{x}{7} = \frac{x^2}{14}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              As before, you can multiply then cancel:
              <me>
                \frac{3x}{2}\cdot \frac{-13}{5x} = \frac{3x(-13)}{2(5x)} =
                -\frac{-39\cancel x}{10\cancel x} = -\frac{-39}{10}
              </me>
              or you can cancel, then multiply
              <me>
                \frac{3\cancel{x}}{2}\cdot \frac{-13}{5\cancel{x}} = \frac{3(-13)}{2(5)} =
                -\frac{-39}{10}
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              I'll do this one in a fair amount of detail:
              <me>
                x\left(\frac{1+\sfrac 1x}{x+\sfrac 1x}\right) = \sfrac{x}{1}
                \left(\frac{1+\sfrac 1x}{x+\sfrac 1x}\right) = \frac{x\left(1+\sfrac
                1x\right)}{x+\sfrac 1x} = \frac{x+\sfrac xx}{x+\sfrac{1}{x}} =
                \frac{x+1}{x+\sfrac 1x}
              </me>
              To cancel the last <m>\sfrac 1x</m> we multiply
              the top and the bottom of this last fraction by <m>x</m> and simplify:
              <me>
                \sfrac xx \cdot \frac{x+1}{x+\sfrac 1x} =
                \frac{x(x+1)}{x\left(x+\sfrac 1x\right)} = \frac{x(x+1)}{x^2+1}
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</section>

